QK Exercises

Kiffer et al. (2015) were interested in the nutritional value of leaves from native and introduced trees to “shredders” – invertebrate larvae in streams that help to break down organic material. They focused on one shredder species, the caddisfly Triplectides gracilis and its relationship between four native species and the blue gum Eucalyptus globulus, an introduced species grown in plantations. They exposed individual caddisflies to one of these species, and recorded their growth; their Figure 1 shows the experimental setup. They measured the tibial length of each larva at weekly intervals, and used a conversion equation to estimate the animal’s biomass at this time.

Preliminaries

First, load the required packages

Get data file

kiffer <- read.csv("data/kiffer_growth.csv")
set_sum_contrasts()
setting contr.sum globally: options(contrasts=c('contr.sum', 'contr.poly'))
# Start by treating week as continuous predictor
kiffer$subject <- factor(kiffer$subject)
kiffer_na <-na.omit(kiffer)

#Deprecated code using gather; replaced by chunk with pivot_longer below
kiffer1 <- gather(kiffer, week, growth, week1:week5, factor_key=FALSE)
kiffer1$weekno <- revalue(kiffer1$week, c("week1"="1", "week2"="2", "week3"="3", "week4"="4", "week5"="5"))
kiffer1$week <- factor(kiffer1$week, ordered= TRUE)
class(kiffer1$weekno)
kiffer1_na<-gather(kiffer_na, week, growth, week1:week5, factor_key=FALSE)
kiffer1_na$weekno <- revalue(kiffer1_na$week, c("week1"="1", "week2"="2", "week3"="3", "week4"="4", "week5"="5"))
kiffer1_na$week <- factor(kiffer1_na$week, ordered= TRUE)
class(kiffer1_na$weekno)
kiffer1 <-  pivot_longer(kiffer,
    cols = starts_with("week"), 
    names_to = "weekno", 
    names_prefix = "week",
    names_transform = list(weekno = as.integer),
    values_to = "growth",
    values_drop_na = TRUE,
  )
head(kiffer1)
kiffer1_na <-  pivot_longer(kiffer_na,
    cols = starts_with("week"), 
    names_to = "weekno", 
    names_prefix = "week",
    names_transform = list(weekno = as.integer),
    values_to = "growth",
    values_drop_na = TRUE,
  )

Data file is a bit messy, with some missing values. Not a problem when time is continuous, but an issue with categorical. We’ll opt for deletion of subjects with missing values. This is a bit tricky with the data file in longitudinal format, as we need to track down any subject with a missing value for one of the weeks, so it was done on the wide file read in at the start

Run with ez to get GG and HF adjustments easily

# manually remove missing values
kiffer1_na$weekno<-as.factor(kiffer1_na$weekno)
ezkiffer1 <- ezANOVA(data=kiffer1_na, dv=growth, wid=subject, within=weekno, between=species, type=3, detailed=TRUE)
